Show HN: Gowebrtc.com
text:
Hello Hacker News!

I'm excited to share my latest project, https://www.gowebrtc.com, with you. It's a free WebRTC broadcast server that allows developers to easily add live video, audio, and data to their apps. I built it using the powerful open-source Pion WebRTC project as a base.

My main focus is on enabling one-to-many broadcasts, as well as allowing for quick switching of streams using unique publisher IDs. This makes it easy for viewers to navigate between different streams and find the content they're interested in.

I'm eager to hear your thoughts on the project and would be happy to answer any questions you might have. Thanks for checking it out!

Ask HN: What closed-source license can work for a business like renting plugins?
text:
Lets say there are open-source options for a niche market but you see business potential in offering a closed source library to do the same (or slightly more) but more "solid" for production conditions (scale/load/network volume, etc).

What kind of licensing should one use for a business model that wants to scale with this?

Let's say for 1 plugin running in 1 container it has to pay a yearly renewable licensing fee of X. For 42 of these it would be x42 (or whatever proportion/discount of that gets negotiated).

I have no experience with software licensing and several plugin ideas to experiment to see if they have business potential but they will need a solid license. I'd appreciate the advice of who does. Thanks a lot.

When will a 64 bit int run out of space to store epoch time?
text:
"A 64-bit integer can store a range of values from -9,223,372,036,854,775,808 to 9,223,372,036,854,775,807. If we assume that the epoch time is stored in Unix format, which is the number of seconds since January 1, 1970, at 00:00:00 UTC, then a 64-bit integer can represent times up to:

9,223,372,036,854,775,807 seconds / 60 seconds per minute / 60 minutes per hour / 24 hours per day / 365.25 days per year = 292,277,026,596 years

This means that a 64-bit integer will run out of space to store epoch time on or around the year 292,277,026,596 AD. However, it's worth noting that this is well beyond the predicted lifespan of our sun and the Earth, so this is not a practical concern for most applications."

Dang ChatGPT you state the end of the sun and Earth like it's no big deal!
